title: Influence of incomplete fusion on complete fusion: Observation of a large incomplete fusion fraction at E~ 5-7 MeV/nucleon

x4freetext: Influence of incomplete fusion on complete fusion:
Observation of a large incomplete fusion fraction
at E~ 5-7 MeV/nucleon

x4freetext: The self-supporting 159-Tb (abundance==99.99%)
targets of thickness ~0.83 mg/cm*2 were prepared by
rolling method and the 169-Tm (abundance=100%)
targets of 0.65 mg/cm*2 thickness, using
vaccum-evaporation technique. The Al-backing of
169-Tm targets served as energy degrader as well a
catcher foil during the irradiations. The 159-Tb
targets were backed by thick Al-cathers of ~2
mg/cm*2 thickness to trap the recoiling nuclei. The
targets were cut into the size of 1.2 x 1.2 cm*2 and
were pasted on Al-holders having concentric hole of
1.0 cm diameter. The Al-holders were used for rapid
dissipation of heat produced during the irradiations.
The evaporation residues populated in each
target-catcher foil assembly via complete and/or
incomplete fusion of 16-O were identified by counting
the induced activities using high resolution HPGe
gamma-ray spectrometer of 100 c.c. active volume
coupled to PC through CAMAC based FREEDOM software.
Particle-gamma coincidence technique
for various projectile-target combinations over wide
projectile energy range has been employed for
precise measurement and analysis of excitation
functions, recoil range distributions, and spin
distributions of residues populated via complete
and/or incomplete fusion. Recoil-catcher technique
followed by off-line gamma-ray spectrometry has been
also employed in the measurement.
Two stacks each containing four and five samples of
159-Tb were irradiated at beam energies ~87 and 95
MeV, while two stacks of 169-Tm targets having four
and three samples each where irradiated at energies
~92 and 95 MeV by an 16-O beam. The beam current was
monitored ~30-50 nA for both the systems in all
irradiations.
Data analysis have been performed using
FREEDOM software for nuclear data analysis. Area
under the peaks of identified gamma-lines of
evaporation residues were used to estimate the count
rate followed by production probability measurement.
A FORTRAN program EXP-SIGMA has been used for the
determination of the production cross sections of
evaporation residues. In order to examine the extent to
which the observed quantities are described in terms of
the equilibrated decay of 175-Ta* and 185-Ir* populated
in the interaction of 16-O with 159-Tb and 169-Tm
within the energy range ~75-95 MeV, the presently
measured excitations functions have been compared with
those calculated using statistical model code PACE2
(based on Hauser-Feshbach theory). The code PACE2 is
based on statistical approach of CN deexcitation by
Monte Carlo procedure. The angular momentum projections
are calculated at each stage of deexcitation. The
angular momentum conservation is explicitly taken into
account at each step, and the CF cross sections are
calculated using BASS formula. It may, however, be
pointed out that the ICF process is not taken into
account in code PACE2. Hence, the enhancement of
experimentally measured production cross sections as
compared to the theoretical predictions may be
attributed to the incomplete fusion process.
The non uniform thickness of samples that may
lead to the uncertainty  in the determination of
the number of target nuclei. It is estimated that
the error in the thickness of the sample material is
less than 1%. Fluctuations in the beam current may
result in the variation of incident flux, proper
care has been taken to keep the beam current
constant as far as possible and, correction in flux
determination from the fluctuations in beam current
has been applied.
Uncertainty in the determination of
geometry dependent spectrometer efficiency. The
error in the efficiency determination due to the
statistical fluctuations in counts is estimated to
be less than 2%. In this measurements both the
sample and the catcher foils were counted together
and hence, the losses due to the recoiling of nuclei
is avoided.
The dead time of the spectrometer was kept
<(or=)10% by suitably adjusting sample detector
distance.

The experimental data has been compared with the
prediction of theoretical model code PACE2. The
enhancement in the production cross sections, in case
of alpha-emission channels (after correcting the
precursor contribution, if any), as compared to
PACE2 calculations has been attributed to the
incomplete fusion reaction. The incomplete fusion
fraction is found to be <(or=)1% at ~75 MeV, while
it is approaching ~20% of the total fusion cross
section at ~95 MeV for 16-O + 159-Tb system.
However, the incomplete fusion fraction is found to
be <(or=)10% at ~75 MeV and observed to be ~30% 0f
the total fusion cross section at ~95 MeV for 16-O +
169-Tm system. It may however be pointed out that
the incomplete fusion fraction is also found to be
more in mass symmetric systems, though, the
projectile structure effect appears to play
significant role in the systematics but this
conjecture needs to be confirmed by further
experimental data.
